ial theory is of particular importance. Yet do these social changes that have a deep impact on life and body, communication and work as well as on our concept of ourselves and the world, really indicate an inner-worldly trans-human salvation? The authors of this book provide perspectives that take these processes of social change seriously and demand that they be designed in a humane manner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Nov 2018) 4aArt. 4aBody. 4aCultural Studies. 4aCyborg. 4aDigitalisierung. 4aDigitalization. 4aHuman. 4aKultursoziologie. 4aKulturwissenschaft. 4aKunst. 4aKörper. 4aMensch. 4aOptimierung. 4aOptimization. 4aReligion. 4aSociology of Culture. 4aSociology of Technology. 4aSociology. 4aSoziologie. 4aTechnik. 4aTechniksoziologie. 4aTechnology.1 aFlessner, Bernd, eauthor.1 aHurka, Herbert M., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2018z9783110603231oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.14361/9783839442876zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783839442876.jpg  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23-DSWb2018